🧠 OS Concept 1: Process States
1️⃣ Simple Idea

A process is not always running.
It keeps changing states.

Main states:

New → Ready → Running → Waiting → Terminated
🧠 Real-World Analogy

Think of you in a job interview process:

Applied → (New)

Waiting in hall → (Ready)

Giving interview → (Running)

Waiting for result → (Waiting)

Selected/Rejected → (Terminated)

⚙️ Why This Exists

CPU is limited (only one core executes one process at a time).

So OS must:

keep some processes waiting

run one process at a time

switch between them

⚙️ How It Works
🔹 New

Process just created

🔹 Ready

Waiting for CPU

🔹 Running

Currently executing

🔹 Waiting (Blocked)

Waiting for I/O (like file read)

🔹 Terminated

Execution finished

🔗 Connection to Programming

When you run a program:

python app.py

OS creates process → New

waits for CPU → Ready

executes → Running

reads file → Waiting

finishes → Terminated

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Difference between Ready and Waiting state?

👉 Ready = waiting for CPU
👉 Waiting = waiting for I/O

🧠 Memory Trick
Ready = CPU wait
Waiting = Resource wait
🧠 OS Concept 2: Context Switching

Now the most important concept 🔥

1️⃣ Simple Idea

CPU switches from one process to another.

This switching is called:

👉 Context Switching

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Imagine you are:

watching YouTube

coding

chatting

You switch tasks constantly.

Before switching, your brain remembers:

what you were doing

where you stopped

That memory = context

⚙️ Why It Exists

CPU can run only one process at a time (per core).

But we want:

Multitasking experience

So OS quickly switches processes.

⚙️ How It Works Internally

Step-by-step:

1️⃣ Save current process data into PCB
2️⃣ Load next process data from PCB
3️⃣ CPU starts executing new process

Process A → (save state)
Process B → (load state)
🔗 Connection to PCB (Day 1)

PCB stores:

Registers
Program counter
State

During context switch:

👉 PCB is used to save & restore process

⚠️ Important Point

Context switching is overhead (no real work done).

So too many switches = slow system.

🎯 Placement Question

Q: What is context switching?

👉 Saving current process state and loading another process state to switch CPU execution.

🧠 Memory Trick
Context switch = Pause → Save → Load → Resume
⚙️ COA Concept 3: Instruction Cycle

Now we go inside CPU deeply.

1️⃣ Simple Idea

CPU works in a loop:

👉 Fetch → Decode → Execute

🔥 This is the HEART of computer

\text{Instruction Cycle: Fetch \rightarrow Decode \rightarrow Execute}

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Think of cooking:

1️⃣ Read recipe → (Fetch)
2️⃣ Understand → (Decode)
3️⃣ Cook → (Execute)

⚙️ Step-by-Step Working
1️⃣ Fetch

CPU gets instruction from memory.

Using:

👉 Program Counter (PC)

2️⃣ Decode

Control unit understands instruction.

Example:

ADD R1 R2
3️⃣ Execute

ALU performs operation.

R1 + R2
🔗 Connection to Registers

PC → next instruction

IR → current instruction

Registers → hold data

🎯 Placement Question

Q: What are stages of instruction cycle?

👉 Fetch, Decode, Execute

🧠 Memory Trick
FDE = Fetch Decode Execute
⚙️ COA Concept 4: Addressing Modes

This is asked a lot in interviews.

1️⃣ Simple Idea

Addressing mode =
👉 How CPU finds data for instruction

🧠 Real-World Analogy

If I say:

👉 "Bring book"

You ask:

Which book?

Where is it?

That is addressing.

⚙️ Types (Important Ones)
1️⃣ Immediate Addressing

Data is inside instruction

MOV R1, 5

👉 Value = 5 (direct)

2️⃣ Direct Addressing

Instruction contains memory address

MOV R1, [1000]

👉 Go to memory 1000

3️⃣ Register Addressing

Data is in register

MOV R1, R2

👉 Use R2 value

4️⃣ Indirect Addressing

Register contains address

MOV R1, [R2]

👉 R2 → address → data

⚙️ Why Addressing Modes Exist

To:

make instructions flexible

improve performance

reduce memory usage

🔗 Connection to Programming

In C:

int x = 5;
int *p = &x;

👉 pointer = indirect addressing

🎯 Placement Question

Q: What is immediate vs direct addressing?

👉 Immediate = value inside instruction
👉 Direct = value from memory address

🧠 Memory Trick
Immediate = instant value
Direct = direct memory
Register = inside CPU
Indirect = address of address
